---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <h2>What insurance covers a pedestrian accident?</h2>
  <p>The at-fault driver&rsquo;s bodily injury liability (BIL) insurance is the primary source. If the driver is uninsured or underinsured, the pedestrian&rsquo;s own uninsured/underinsured motorist (UM/UIM) coverage applies — even though the pedestrian was on foot. PIP (personal injury protection) in no-fault states also covers medical bills regardless of fault.</p>
  <h2>What if the driver fled the scene?</h2>
  <p>A hit-and-run pedestrian accident is treated as an uninsured motorist claim under the pedestrian&rsquo;s own UM coverage. Most states require physical contact with the unidentified vehicle (or a witness) to qualify for UM benefits in a hit-and-run. Report the accident to police immediately to document the hit-and-run.</p>
  <h2>Does a pedestrian ever bear fault?</h2>
  <p>Yes. Jaywalking, crossing outside a crosswalk, crossing against a red signal, or being distracted by a phone can reduce a pedestrian&rsquo;s recovery under comparative fault rules. However, even partially at-fault pedestrians often recover substantial amounts because driver speed and inattention are usually the dominant causes of severe injuries.</p>
  <h2>How much is the average pedestrian accident settlement?</h2>
  <p>Pedestrian settlements vary enormously by injury severity. Minor injuries: $15,000–$50,000. Moderate injuries: $50,000–$200,000. Severe injuries (multiple fractures, hospitalization): $200,000–$1,000,000. Catastrophic injuries (TBI, paralysis): $1,000,000+. Insurance policy limits often constrain recovery.</p>
  <h2>Do I need an attorney?</h2>
  <p>For serious injuries, yes. Insurance adjusters for at-fault drivers are experienced at minimizing payouts. Pedestrian accident attorneys typically take cases on contingency (30–33% of recovery) and can significantly increase the settlement amount. The attorney also handles UM/UIM claims if the driver is underinsured.</p>
</BaseLayout>
